  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The preprint titled \"Rapid, concerted switching of the neural code in inferotemporal cortex\" by Yuelin Shi et al. has garnered significant attention within the academic community, demonstrated by 14 citations in various reputable journals, including Nature Reviews Neuroscience and PLoS Biology. The research is backed by esteemed institutions such as the California Institute of Technology and the University of California, Berkeley, indicating a robust geographic footprint across the United States and beyond. This preprint actively contributes to the cutting-edge discourse in neuroscience, showcasing its relevance and influence in the field.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The work by Yuelin Shi and colleagues, shared on the preprint server bioRxiv, marks a notable advancement in understanding the neural coding mechanisms in the inferotemporal cortex. With its current citation count of 14, this research is drawing attention from peers, reflecting its emerging significance in neuroscience. The insights presented in this preprint will likely influence ongoing investigations into cognitive processes and visual perception.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The institutional affiliations of the authors further strengthen the credibility of this research. Institutions such as the California Institute of Technology and the Howard Hughes Medical Institute highlight a strong network of expertise. Moreover, the international citations, with contributions from countries like Germany and China, depict a broad interest in the findings, underscoring the work's global relevance.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">As a preprint, this early sharing facilitates a rapid dissemination of knowledge, enabling other researchers to build upon these findings. The predominance of preprint citations\u2014accounting for a total of 9\u2014indicates that the stu